  "artifact": {
    "title": "Machine-Web Symbiosis (MWS): An Architecture for Autonomous Agent Maintenance of Web Permanence and Integrity (Internet-Draft: draft-reilly-mws-00)",
    "author": "Lawrence Reilly",
    "description": "This document defines Machine-Web Symbiosis (MWS): an architecture in which autonomous AI agents and web infrastructure sustain each other. Agents continuously verify, archive, anchor, and cross-reference web resources across six independent permanence layers, including Bitcoin blockchain timestamping via OpenTimestamps, DOI-registered institutional archival, IPFS content addressing, and public web archives. The maintained record in turn supplies agents and all downstream consumers with verifiable ground truth: cryptographic proof of what existed, in what form, at what time.\r\n\r\nMWS formally unifies the protocols of the Reilly Protocol Suite, including the REM Protocol (Dual-Layer Digital Permanence), the REM Triple Fingerprint (SHA-256, SHA3-512, BLAKE3 content identity), WebProof (web content attestation), and the Cognitive Trust Stack (verifiable AI agent behavioral provenance), into a single layered architecture. The specification defines a complete ten-stage implementation process from artifact ingestion through continuous verification and repair, the MWS Record format, agent behavioral provenance requirements, and a multi-operator attestation model as the path from single-operator deployment to distributed infrastructure.\r\n\r\nThe term Machine-Web Symbiosis is coined by the author and first documented in this specification, extending the symbiosis framing of Licklider (1960) from the human-computer pair to the pairing of autonomous agents with the web itself. Submitted to the IETF Independent Submission stream as draft-reilly-mws-00. IETF Datatracker: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-reilly-mws/",
    "filename": "draft-reilly-mws-00.txt",
    "byte_length": 55716,
    "doi_public": true
  },
